ere and me sister looked and she said, oh, I've got a fish - she said. Oh I said, so have I. And when we looked she says - poor Father Christmas she says - he must have been hungry - he's bit the tail off my fish. And when we went downstairs - I heard me 
-
 I remember me father saying well that's funny to me mother - over the fish, and I - they never knew to the day they died that I'd bit the end off that fish - and me sister either. But from then - on I realized then that there was no Father Christmas. And
 it was your mother and father that were doing it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 
What type of people do you think your parents hoped you'd grow up to be? Did they bring you up to think that certain things were important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 Well, I was always brought up this way. Very, v
ery comfortable and me father always used to say wherever you go, whatever friends you make, let your friends be our friends. Never stand at street corners. Always bring your friends home - doesn't matter who they are - always bring them home. And in the 
w
inter with me being able to play the piano in them days we used to come home and Sunday we used to have a musical evening. Yes. Mother and father sometimes - used to go perhaps about nine o'clock - for a drink - they just went to the Stag - just lowerdown
 in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14512446\charrsid814818 E}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 
dge Lane at that time and many a time father's been that - interested and that delighted with us all that he's not gone out and mother's got really mad - annoyed about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 She liked him to go out did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 Well, Sunday night was the only nigh
t that she got an hour out 'cos we used to be open 'til twelve o'clock in them days. The cinema was at the corner - at the corner. The Seedley cinema - was pictures then at the corner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 What year would this be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 Well, we went in the shop in 1911. 
You see, so it was like as it went on. Even in the - like the first world war. But - the - she like wanted to go out because she - she wouldn't go out without me dad, you see, they always went together. Always went you never found one without the other - 
just like - like husband and myself, it's like as if traditions have carried on - yes. Always went out together, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 What did they think of swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 
Well, I never - I can honestly say that - I never heard - what you can call bad language. I al
ways remember me mother one time saying something and it was swine and I - me dad jumped up and he says - don't use anything like that, he said, it's disgusting, he said, where the children are. And I - I'd only be about seven I think. And I - I just can'
t
 think what it was over - whether it was over come with combing the plaits and things out because we used to have them in as I say Friday night and we used to have ribbons at each side and there used to be - well, Sunday morning, and it used to take her a
 
blooming hour to get the plaits undone and your hair combed out and it - it used to be like a busby - it'd be that frizzy. But she used to think it was marvellous. Yes, everybody used to comment about - and - yes, and with me being a bright auburn like an
d me sister was darker it was such a contrast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 
Do you ever remember any particular occasion when you were punished and what it was for and how you felt about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 
Yes, I do. And - it was - one Sunday as I - after dinner. And after dinner mother us
ed to bake - perhaps pies - apple pies or jam pies - and this particular Sunday she decided to - make - a - a deep custard in this and she'd put - left them on the table for the oven to get right and she'd gone into - I think the lady - the lady next door
 had knocked or something and she had gone in there. And me sisters at one side and I'm at the other and we're looking and all at once I just took a swoop at this custard you know - drink out of the - and of course when I did it my sister had a go -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 You took some of the liquid you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 
Yes, the liquid - the milk. She's at one side of the table and I'm at the other. And - I started it off first - yes, of course me sister followed suit so that when mother come - came back and - really to go in the 
oven - I - there was very, very little - liquid in. I didn't get chance to fill it up with water as I intended to do. And I always remember getting a - getting a real pasting for that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 How did you feel about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 Oh it was - I - me that did it and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 You didn't mind being punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 
Well I knew I'd done wrong but I didn't expect the blooming good hiding I got. No. So I was pushed upstairs and there I had to stop. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 Would you think you got the ideas about what was right and wrong a
nd how to behave from your mother or your father or did you feel that one played a more important part than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 
Well, I think - I think mother more or less. Yes, because - there was a big family of their - them - that same as I say the sisters
 and - they'd really - been they were - they kind of all had their own fixed jobs - their - own fixed ways as the as they got settled after me - me grandfather was discharged from the Army and that. And of course - he was an army man and then he came out 
of the Army he kind of - he was really a hard drinker - like. And then he'd perhaps go - me grandmother would bring the priest along to him you know - they did in them days and he'd get -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 She }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14512446\charrsid814818 thought}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818  the priest could do something with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 He'd g
ive him a good talking to - well, Patrick you shouldn't do this and Patrick you shouldn't do the other. And he'd go on the water wagon then for months, you see, and there'd be really pretty comfortable and I think with me mother and her sisters like with 
b
eing - her - their mother had them so much under control that my mother used to - treat us practically the same. She'd more to say in it, you see, than what me father - had and then - yes - and then of course if mother wasn't out like nursing she was at h
o
me all the day. Well I'd see more of me mother really than I would of me dad, like, because - some - we'd come home from school, well, many a time me dad'd be late, he perhaps wouldn't have his dinner hour from half past one perhaps well, half past two or
 
sometimes - if they were that busy such as summer months, when trade an everything was so busy, he perhaps wouldn't come home at all to his dinner. Mother used to leave it between two plates. And then if he'd to go out delivering if shops sent - yes, afte
r
 he'd done his - he'd do his weighing out and he'd take one of the carts and horses out and he deliver it himself. And he'd call back and have pick - have his dinner then - and back again to work - many a time it's been - eight o'clock at night - perhaps 
when he's finished. Well I've been ready for bed when he's come in you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 So actually he just washed the tripe in this big trough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 
He weighed it - it was all ready for weighing out. He used to bring it out and swing it on the scales - me dad. He was what they called the weigher out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 Not a tripe dresser?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 
Yes. Well he went through the trade - it was his father who started on Hyed Road and it was me father's father that really first started it. And then they - they got it up - Uncle Fre
d was the next and my father started and they started in a boiler at the back of two ought eight Regent Road - that was first and then they - back of two ought eight Regent Road. Yes. And then they got a little - an ordinary big boiler - big - like a boil
er - some sort of a boiler they had - of course - I tell you but - I heard my father say - they boiled it and that and they dressed it on a long trestle table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 Did tripe have to be boiled?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 Oh yes, they - they cow - what they call cows bellies. Ye
s. Well - used to sling them and cut them open you see. Oh no. It had - yes, cut what they call the bellies and - then they used to boil it - they started like that. And then they got this little place at the back - as you go by - round by Leonards - two-
t
wo-two. Well that first little white building was what they called the weighing out shop. That was med dad's place and the office was just at the back. So - 'ti - oit - they prospered so well that they got the full row and they got the stables at the back
 of that for the horses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 Did your dad have to buy the full beast just to get the stomach out of it?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 
They used to buy - Uncle Fred - he used - they had - they used to - they used to buy - I don't know whether they come from the - whether they got 
them from the abbatoires - which I should imagine that they'd get the bellies from the abbatoires and they used sling them but when I worked there they used to come in big bags - the bellies - and you used to take them out and sling them, the men, and the
y used to cut them - down -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 How do you mean sling them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 
Put them onto hooks you see. In a certain way like - there was - like for cutting. And then they were boiled - well the boiling shop was upstairs - great big boilers. They used to have.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 You mean he used to cut the eatable part of the stomach out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 No, they used to cut it all out 'cos it was nearly all eatable.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 It all had to be boiled?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 
All had to be boiled - yes. And what was termed the black tripe - that was the dirtiest part of a beast. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 This is the most expensive to buy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 
Yes, but a lot of people - if they saw it - if they did see the processes and everything they'd never touch black tripe. Again, because we've been up to here in cow dirt.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 Off the black tripe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 
Yes, you used to have to put your hands right the way up and turn it inside out to clean it. Yes, and the bottom part of it was like the frill - what they call the frill and the top part was what they call the black top that and it used to 
be scalded - cleaned and well cleaned before it was boiled. But it was a marvellous thing to see. To watch the processes that it goes through and when it was boiled it used to come out all - then it had to be - it used to be scraped when it was that - and
 we used to scrape -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 With a knife?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 
No, used to have scrapers - like a scraper that you scrape wallpaper - yes, and a handle on it and there was a certain way and there used to be what they called the honeycomb - yes, there was the honeycomb. Well
 - that had to be specially - on account of the little holes that had to be thoroughly clean. There was the face piece - there was the cross piece and there was what they called the seam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 Why was it called a face piece?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 Because - it was - there 
was no really seam - it was a very plain tripe - it wasn't - as you see tripe like a bit - that thick seam, that's - that was the top - that was doubled over where the fat is. But the face piece itself was what you call a flat tripe - there was no - nothi
ng on it - it just looked like a piece of leather to look at it - white leather. But still it was very tasty - it was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 There was the face piece and then the cross piece?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 Cross piece yes. Well the cross piece was a piece and the seam - you have t
o cut it in the centre, you see, and you got the seam at both ends. The seam came right in the centre of these two pieces, you see, and then the seam itself was the biggest and that for - that's the double fold as you see it and the seam running along the
 
top and the double fold. And there used to be diff - oh there's a special way to cut it but they don't do it today. They don't - well a face piece, you used to cut it to the seam - that was nearly all what you can call flat seam and it just at one end it 
w
as thick. Well you see, you'd cut that off and then a cross piece you'd cut this like in the centre - you'd start from the centre, cut it in the centre and work each end. And - the - the vein as we called it - that was the double - leaf - well you'd cut -
 you'd double that over and you'd start and cut right up. Well a lot of people today, in a tripe shop, if you ask for seam, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8159037\charrsid814818 you\rquote ll}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818  see them sometimes, I've seen them, cut the seam along the top. Well, that's ridiculous. Because you're not equalising your se
am you see. Where if you went in a shop and you asked for half a pound of seam and I served you well that'd be doubled over - and I'd just cut it from the bottom right up as you got a piece of the seam at the top, and that's the seam you see. Well they do
n't do it today in these shops - I've watched 'em do it. And you can -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 And you helped in this business?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8396337 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 How old were you when you started in this? You told me first of all you w}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14512446\charrsid814818 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 nt to buttonholing didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10686843 LB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818 I went to - I work
ed at Mortons corset place on Regent Road first - yes, I went there 1911 I think it would be - yes. Yes, ladies outfitters it was as they call it but it was a corset place - they came from off }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8159037\charrsid814818 Old field}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14037617\charrsid814818  Road, they was very well known.
